headline: CNN News Central
subHeadline: Man Accused Of Hiding On Flight After Using Pic Of Ticket To Board; Last Former Mississippi Police Officers Being Sentenced For Brutal Tortures Of 2 Innocent Black Men; CNN Confronts NC GOP Nominee Who Called For Obama To Be Executed; March Madness Fever Grips The Nation. Aired 2:30-3p ET

utterances.speaker: DAVID SOUCIE, CNN SAFETY ANALYST
utterances.sentences: But the fact is this threat, he went all the way through, there had to be multiple failures. He got himself through that first one by having a ticket to a different flight.But the second layer is when the gate agent checks it. as they check in. You've done it. You can see it. and it gains and says, yes, everything's OK. But if there's a duplicate ticket that's scanned, that system is designed to make that warning at that point before anybody ever gets down the down the runway into the airplane. So there's definitely some vulnerabilities in that system, whether it's human failure, whether it's a systemic failure, that is yet to be determined, but it is a serious failure in my mind.

utterances.speaker: BORIS SANCHEZ, CNN HOST
utterances.sentences: Yes. David, while we have you, we also want to ask about a report regarding federal regulators conducting a privacy review of data policies at Americas top-10 airlines.What does that review entail? What do you think they might find?

utterances.speaker: SOUCIE
utterances.sentences: Well, it has a lot to do -- there's several different tiers of it. But if you think about just the HIPAA regulations, about regulatory information or information about your own personal health.Now, if there's a HIPAA violation, which there could possibly be here, if they're asking for health information about passengers or even employees of the airline, they can ask that information. If that information is transferred or moved without the permission of the person that's -- that owns that data, which is you, for your own health care information. Then that can be moved and it's actually a federal crime and it can be a civil penalty of up to $25,000 to 35,000 dollars per event. So it's a very serious thing as well. And privacy of information in today's world -- as you know, I had my I.D. stolen from me and I have to use different Social Security numbers and everything else. So it's definitely possible to happen and it does. But when it happens with your own personal information, that becomes very serious and it needs to be looked at. Again, it's another one of these threats or vulnerabilities that exist in air travel.

utterances.speaker: SANCHEZ
utterances.sentences: Yes, better to get out ahead of it now before it becomes a much broader problem.David Soucie, always appreciate the perspective. Thanks.

utterances.speaker: SOUCIE
utterances.sentences: All right. Thank you.

utterances.speaker: ERICA HILL, CNN HOST
utterances.sentences: In Mississippi, the last of the so-called Goon Squad deputies is being sentenced today for torturing two black men.The gruesome details of these racially motivated beatings, torture, sexual assaults, even a mock execution, have played out in court. All six of the former law enforcement officers pleaded guilty back in August to federal charges. Attorney General Merrick Garland spoke out against their heinous acts, attacks earlier this week. This morning, former Rankin County Deputy Brett McAlpin, who you see there on the left, was sentenced to more than 27 years in prison. Now he was the highest-ranking officer on the scene. And soon, the man on the right, that is former Richland Police Officer Joshua Hartfield, will learn his fate. CNN senior national correspondent, Ryan Young, joins us from Jackson, Mississippi, where he has been following this case. But also, you've been in court throughout these proceedings, Ryan. What more did you hear in court today?

utterances.speaker: RYAN YOUNG, CNN NATIONAL CORRESPONDENT
utterances.sentences: Look, I think some of us are still shocked by some of the new details that were learning. A team of us have been following the story for almost a year now.And today, when we talk about the racial motivated part of this, what we are also learning is there are plenty of people who are white, who are showing up to now complain about these officers and the role they played. We learned that the fourth-highest-ranking member of the sheriff's department -- that's Brett McAlpin -- he actually showed up off duty in civilian clothes and watched all this go down. Eddie Parker really put it -- summed it up really well. He said, "Everyone's begging for mercy now, but that night, while we were being tortured, beaten, waterboarded, tased over and over, shot, we begged for our lives and no one felt for us." So you can understand the pain that's still going on here. Gets 27 years. On top of all that, what a lot of people sort of were concerned about or even talking about in the gallery was the fact that McAlpin's attorney was a black man. Take a listen to some of the defense and some of the reasons why he thought his client should have gotten less time. (BEGIN VIDEOTAPE)

utterances.speaker: AAFRAM SELLERS, ATTORNEY FOR BRETT MCALPIN
utterances.sentences: I think for Mr. McAlpin to be sentenced to more time than the actual person who -- who shot Mr. Jenkins, I fought -- I fought against that.But unfortunately, you respect the court's ruling when they make a ruling. But you know, mostly in the work we put into this, you know, even though you're disappointed that you didn't receive the outcome that you wanted, but I do think, again, the court has the final say in this. (END VIDEO CLIP)

utterances.speaker: HILL
utterances.sentences: Yes, Ryan, it is so important to stay on this. I'm glad you stayed on it for so long and continue to bring us those details. Thank you.A candidate who wants to run North Carolinas public schools confronted with her controversial and, at times, violent posts online, including a call to execute top Democrats. So what did she say when our own Shimon Prokupecz caught up with her? That's next. (COMMERCIAL BREAK)

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: Hi, Ms. Morrow. How are you?MICHELE MORROW (R), NOMINEE FOR NORTH CAROLINA SUPERINTENDENT OF PUBLIC INSTRUCTION: Hi. I'm doing fine.

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: All right. How did it go in there?

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: Hey, it went great.

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: Yes?

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: It went great.

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: You feeling good?

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: Yes.Who are you guys with?

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: I'm Shimon Prokupecz. I'm with CNN.

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: Oh, have you been parked in my neighborhood by any chance?

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: We've been trying to talk to you, yes.

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: OK. Well, you can --(CROSSTALK)

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: -- you can go through my campaign. Thanks.

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: So -- I understand, but I have you now. So, why don't we talk now?

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: No. No need.

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: Why not?Well, I want to ask you, do you still stand -- (CROSSTALK)

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: Because it's -- it's late and we're -- (INAUDIBLE)-- now.

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: I'm not talking to you, ma'am.

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: OK.

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: Do you still stand by your comments about former President Barack Obama and that he should be executed, calling for the death of other presidents? Do you stand by that? Do you stand by those comments?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: We're doing -- (INAUDIBLE).

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: Have a good night.

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: Do you stand by --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: We have no comment.

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: Thanks.

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: -- what you've said about the public education --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: No comment.

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: -- system and that it needs to be destroyed?

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: No comment.

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: Do you stand by that?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: No comment.

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: No comment.

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: Do you understand the concern that people have with this --(CROSSTALK)

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: -- nomination that you now have?

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: No comment.Hey, I have a question, do you vote in North Carolina? Then, keep your eyes on your own paper.

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: Well, let me ask you, I've -- I've --

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: Keep your eyes on your own paper.

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: -- I've read -- I've read papers, though, here, too.

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: Keep your eyes on your own paper.

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: And the concerns that people have with your nomination and the things that you have said.

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: People in New York have concern over my nomination in North Carolina?

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: People all across -- people all across the country.

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: All across -- really?

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: Why are they concerned about North Carolina? Do you know that education is a problem in this entire country? So maybe they need to focus on what's going on in your state of New York, which, by the way, is where I grew up.Maybe they need to focus on what's going on in California, where children are not getting the education that they need. Maybe they need to focus on what they're doing in Michigan. Because right now, in North Carolina, I'm focused on helping the families of North Carolina, for their children to get quality education, for them to be safe, and for us to be sure that our money is going into the classroom rather than bureaucracies. That's what I've been focusing on. That's what I've been fighting for, for the last five years, going to the General Assembly dealing with those issues.

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: Right, but --

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: So, that is why I'm running. So, you can --

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: I understand that, but you have said such hurtful things, too, in terms of the education system --

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: I have to tell you --

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: About transgender students.

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: Everyone is so done with the gotcha moments.

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: This is not a gotcha.

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: It is. This is --

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: This is your own words.

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: Yes, it --

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: Ma'am, these are your own words.

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: This is -- this has nothing to do with education.

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: You have said that the former president --

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: How do you know those are my words?

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: Because you tweeted.

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: You don't have --

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: Are those not your tweets? Do you deny saying that? You have an opportunity now.

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: I am telling you --

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: Do you deny saying that?

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: I am telling you --

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: Are you denying that you said that in those tweets?

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: I am telling you --

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: Have you --

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: -- that I am going to discuss education --

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: Have you talked about the indoctrination of children by teachers?

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: I am telling you --

utterances.speaker: PROKUPECZ
utterances.sentences: Have you talked about that? Have you said that about students?

utterances.speaker: MORROW
utterances.sentences: Have you seen any of me going to the school board for the last five years, because you will have my answer.(END VIDEOTAPE)

utterances.speaker: SANCHEZ
utterances.sentences: And just how detached her comments are from reality as well. I bet she's going to start parking a lot closer to the door.Shimon Prokupecz, appreciate the reporting. Thanks so much. Still to come, basketball fans love March Madness, sometimes more than they love their jobs. More on our annual distraction and obsession in just moments. (COMMERCIAL BREAK)

utterances.speaker: SANCHEZ
utterances.sentences: I hope you did better than Erica and I --(LAUGHTER)

utterances.speaker: SANCHEZ
utterances.sentences: -- who did not make out brackets. I hope yours are ready because March Madness is now in full swing.And while the NCAA tournament is exciting to watch, it can also be a real distraction that pulls us away from our work.

utterances.speaker: HILL
utterances.sentences: Distraction, healthy break, you know, it's all in the framing here.(LAUGHTER)

utterances.speaker: HILL
utterances.sentences: CNN's Harry Enten crunching the numbers on just how many of us may be watching the big dance when the boss isn't looking, or some people watch with losses looking, they don't care.(CROSSTALK)

utterances.speaker: SANCHEZ
utterances.sentences: The boss is probably looking, too.

utterances.speaker: HILL
utterances.sentences: Yes. Good point.

utterances.speaker: ENTEN
utterances.sentences: And I am like a lot of other people. Because the people who filled out a bracket on ESPN or NCAA.com, 25 million or more in 2024. I have that latest stat for you. I just got it.Now of course, I'm also interested in how the nation is picking. Well, most folks -- most folks are like me, guys. Most folks or the plurality of folks picked UConn, 26.1 percent. Who was the most popular non-number--one pick to win at all? How about Arizona at 6.6 percent? I'll note, earlier on in the week, it was Kentucky. So these numbers have been moving around as more and more folks have been picking in their team, unlike you two. And how about the biggest first-round upset? Nearly 48 percent picked Oregon to advance. They're an 11 seed. That's the force most upset ever, ever. So we'll see if the Ducks are able to advance. And then, of course, a bizarre stat. Cinderella in 2020. And 0.3 percent for over 5,000 fans picked all 16 seeds to advance. That's a very bad idea. But I guess some people want to roll the die -- guys?

utterances.speaker: SANCHEZ
utterances.sentences: Yes. Why not? Especially if you do multiple brackets.(CROSSTALK)

utterances.speaker: HILL
utterances.sentences: Right, you can remember back -- I feel like Harry's trying to give us a hard time about not finishing our brackets.

utterances.speaker: ENTEN
utterances.sentences: I am.

utterances.speaker: SANCHEZ
utterances.sentences: Yes. I got distracted. I didn't --(CROSSTALK)

utterances.speaker: ENTEN
utterances.sentences: What are you doing, Boris? Boris, do I need to come down and --(CROSSTALK)

utterances.speaker: ENTEN
utterances.sentences: -- Erica?

utterances.speaker: SANCHEZ
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: HILL
utterances.sentences: Plus, he's got like two more hours of TV later today. But I'm with you, Harry, five hours of live TV. He is a slacker.Let me tell you what I've learned. (LAUGHTER)

utterances.speaker: HILL
utterances.sentences: When I get back to New York, I will fill you in on all the details, Harry.(CROSSTALK)

utterances.speaker: ENTEN
utterances.sentences: I look forward to you dishing with me.(LAUGHTER)

utterances.speaker: SANCHEZ
utterances.sentences: Harry Enten. Thanks a lot, Harry.

utterances.speaker: ENTEN
utterances.sentences: Bye, guys.
